§ 6. Gaius says (iii. 104) that a person in mancipio resembled a slave in being unable to incur an obligation to any one. All that is meant by the text is that between domestic superior and inferior there could be no civilis obligatio ; but if a pater stipulated from his son, or a master from his slave, the son or slave was bound ‘naturally ;¹ ‘patre a filio vel domino a servo stipulatu fideiussor acceptus tenetur’ Dig. 46. 1. 56. r ς cs. Tit. ao. 1 ins.; in the converse case it seems from Dig. loc. cit. that no obligation ol any sort resulted. Contracts made by a filiusfamilias with other per-

. sons than his pater bound him civiliter always, ‘et ob id agi cum eo tanquam cum patrefamilias potest' Dig. 44. 7. 393 buta slave was bound only naturaliter by contracts even with extranei, and the obligatio incurred by an extraneus was also naturalis only, so that the dominus could not sue upon it: ‘ex contractibus [servi] civiliter non obligantur, sed naturaliter ct obligantur et obligant’ Dig. 44 7. 14. Civil obligation between paterfamilias aud filius seems to have been prevented by the latter's want oi proprietary right; when the incapacity was partly re- moved, the rule was pro tanto given up, and in respect os peculium castrense there could be civil obligation and consequently litigation between them: ‘lis nulla nobis esse potest cum eo quem in potestate habemus, nisi ex castrensi peculio’ Dig. 5. 1. 43 cf. Dig. 18. 1. a. pr. 3 47. 2. 52. 4-6. ln respect oi peculium adventitium this relaxation is not recognised in the authorities.
